'''သိခဘာသာ၊ ဘာသာသိခ် (Sikhism)''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|I|k|ɪ|z|əm}}); ပုန်ဇပဳ: ਸਿੱਖੀ or '''Sikhi''' (''{{IAST|Sikkhī}}'',  [ˈsɪkːʰiː], from ਸਿੱਖ, Sikh, မဂွံအဓိပ္ပါယ် 'ကွးသာဝက၊ ညးလ္ၚတ်)  ဂှ် ဒှ်ဘာသာမပတှ်ေကျာ်မွဲဇကု မကၠုင်နူ တမ်မူလ ဒေသပုန်ဇာပ် ပ္ဍဲဒကုတ်တိုက် အိန္ဒိယ<ref group="lower-roman">"Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism and Sikhism originated on the Indian subcontinent."

{{Cite book|last=Moreno, Luis, and César Colino|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N5lpveRnSxEC&pg=PA207|title=Diversity and Unity in Federal Countries}}</ref> ပ္ဍဲအခိင်ကၞောတ် အေဒဳ ၁၅ ဗွဝ်ကၠံ။<ref name="Nesbitt2005">{{Cite book|last=Nesbitt|first=Eleanor M.|title=Sikhism: a very short introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fvTK_CfkeasC}}</ref><ref name="Nirbhai Singh 1990 1–3">{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Nirbhai|url=https://archive.org/details/philosophyofsikh0000nirb|title=Philosophy of Sikhism: Reality and Its Manifestations}}</ref><ref name="Opinderjit Kaur Takhar 2016 147">{{Cite book|last=Takhar|first=Opinderjit Kaur|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UaeoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT147|title=Sikh Identity: An Exploration of Groups Among Sikhs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Religions: Sikhism|url=http://www.bbc.com/religion/religions/sikhism/|last=|first=|date=2014}}</ref><ref name="Cole">{{Cite book|last=Cole|first=William Owen|title=Sikhism and Christianity: A Comparative Study (Themes in Comparative Religion)}}</ref> သိခဘာသာဝွံ ပ္ဍဲဘာသာဇမၞော်ဂမၠိုင် ဒှ်ဘာသာတၟိအိုတ်တုဲ ဒှ်ဘာသာဇၞော်အိုတ် ပ္ဍဲဂၠးတိ မရနုက်ကဵုမသုန်၊ ညးလျုင်ပတှ်ေ နွံၜိုတ် ၂၅ ပြကောဋိကိုဋ် ပ္ဍဲသၞာံ ၂၀၁၉။

သိခဘာသာဂှ် စကတဵုဒှ်ကၠုင် နူကဵု အစာဓရ်ဂုရုနနက်၊ မဒှ် ဂုရုကိုပ်ကၠာအိုတ် (၁၄၆၉-၁၅၃၉)၊ တုဲ ဆက်ကေတ်အာလျိုင်ဒၞာဲညး သီုဖအိုတ် ဂုရု နွံဒစိတ်တၠရ။ ဂုရု မရနုက်ကဵုစှ် ဂုရုဂေါဗိန် သိင်္ဃ (Guru Gobind Singh) (အကြာသၞာံ ၁၆၇၆ - ၁၇၀၈)၊ ဂုရုဂရေန်သဟိဗ် (''Guru Granth Sahib)'' မဒှ် ညးဆက်ဒုင်ကေတ်အာဲညးဂှ် ဒှ်ဂုရုမကြပ်ကဵု ကောန်မၞိဟ်ဂၠိုင်တုဲ ခၞံဗဒှ်ပတိုန် လိက်ဂၠံင်တရဴဓရ်သိခဘာသာရ။<ref name="granthfinalguru">{{Cite book|last=Mann|first=Gurinder Singh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PC4d-5xrysIC|title=The Making of Sikh Scripture|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0-19-513024-9|location=US|pages=21–25, 123–24}}</ref> ဂုရုနနက် ဗ္တောန် ဒဒှ်မဂျိုင်တန်တဴ "နကဵုဘဝမၞုံကဵု ကတိုင်ကၟဟ်၊ ခၞံဗဒှ်၊ ကေုာံ ဒ္ဂေတ်လ္ၚတ် ကုဒဒှ်မဍာံစၟတ် မနွံကဵုသစ္စ၊ မနွံကဵု မထိင်ဒဝ် ကေုာံ အးဇ္ၚးဂှ် ဒှ်အရာသမၠုင်အိုတ် လတူဒ္ဂေတ်လၟေတ်တၞဟ်တအ်ရ၊ တုဲပၠန် မဒက်ပ္တန် ပရေင်ပံင်ကောံ ကုကျာ်၊ မတီကေတ် ပၟိက်ဆန္ဒကျာ်တုဲ ဒ္ဂေတ်ဗက် ဂၠံင်တရဴကျာ်ရ။<ref name="Marwha">{{Cite book|last=Marwaha|first=Sonali Bhatt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ROtEr_QdB3sC|title=Colors of Truth: Religion, Self and Emotions : Perspectives of Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism, Zoroastrianism, Islam, Sikhism and Contemporary Psychology|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|year=2006|isbn=978-81-8069-268-0|pages=205–206}}</ref> ဂုရုဟာဂေါဗိန်( Guru Hargobind)၊ မဒှ်ဂုရု မရနုက်ကဵုတြဴ (ပ္ဍဲအကြာသၞာံ ၁၆၀၆ - ၁၆၄၄) ဂှ် ခၞံဗဒှ်ပတိုန် သဘဴဓဝ် အကြာ ဒတန်မိရိ (ပရေင်ဍုင်ကွာန်) ကေုာံ ဒတန်ပိရိ (ဒ္ဂေတ်ဓရ်) တအ်ရ။<ref name="Marty">{{Cite book|last=Marty|first=Martin E.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=doCmVaOnh_wC|title=Fundamentalisms and the State: Remaking Polities, Economies, and Militance|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1996|isbn=978-0-226-50884-9}}</ref>

The Sikh scripture opens with the ''Mul Mantar'' (ਮੂਲ ਮੰਤਰ), fundamental prayer about ''ik onkar'' (ੴ, 'One God').<ref name="pashauramulmantar">{{Cite book|author=Pashaura Singh|title=The Guru Granth Sahib: Canon, Meaning and Authority|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aiwpDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT101|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-908773-0|pages=101–102}}</ref><ref name="singhaikonkar">{{Cite book|author=Singha, H. S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqIbJz7vMn0C|title=The Encyclopedia of Sikhism (over 1000 Entries)|publisher=Hemkunt|year=2000|isbn=978-81-7010-301-1|pages=20–21, 103}}</ref> The core beliefs of Sikhism, articulated in the ''Guru Granth Sahib'', include faith and  meditation on the name of the one creator; divine unity and equality of all humankind; engaging in ''seva'' ('selfless service'); striving for justice for the  benefit and prosperity of all; and honest conduct and livelihood while living a householder's life.<ref name="Kalsi_Chelsea">{{Cite book|author=Kalsi|title=Sikhism|publisher=Chelsea House|year=|isbn=|pages=41–50}}</ref><ref name="Cole_Sambhi">{{Cite book|author=Cole|title=The Sikhs: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|year=1995|isbn=}}</ref><ref name="Teece 2004 4">{{Cite book|author=Teece|title=Sikhism:Religion in focus|publisher=Black Rabbit Books|year=2004|isbn=978-1-58340-469-0}}</ref> Following this standard, Sikhism rejects claims that any particular religious tradition has a monopoly on  Absolute Truth.<ref group="lower-roman">"Sikhism rejects the view that any particular religious tradition has a monopoly regarding Absolute Truth. Sikhism rejects the practice of converting people to other religious traditions." 

Kalsi, Sewa Singh (2008). ''Sikhism''. London: Kuperard. p.&nbsp;24. {{ISBN|978-1-85733-436-4}}. </ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Reichberg, Gregory M., and Henrik Syse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t3CFAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA672|title=Religion, War, and Ethics: A Sourcebook of Textual Traditions|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-1-139-95204-0|pages=672–74}}</ref>

Sikhism emphasizes ''simran'' (ਸਿਮਰਨ, meditation and remembrance of the words of God),<ref>{{Cite web|title=Where Hinduism and Sikhism meet|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/others/sunday-read/where-hinduism-and-sikhism-meet/articleshow/69705554.cms|last=Pattanaik|first=Devdutt|date=2019|publisher=}}</ref> which can be expressed musically through ''kirtan'', or internally through  <nowiki><i id="mweA">naam japna</i></nowiki> ('meditation on His name') as a means to feel God's presence. It teaches followers to transform the "Five Thieves" (i.e. lust, rage, greed, attachment, and ego).<ref name="Kamala">{{Cite book|last=Nayar|first=Kamala Elizabeth|title=Socially Involved Renunciate, The: Guru Nanak's Discourse to the Nath Yogis|publisher=SUNY Press}}</ref>

The religion developed and evolved in times of religious persecution, gaining converts from both [[ဟိန္ဒူ|Hinduism]] and [[အေဿလာမ်|Islam]].<ref name="Singh2008">
{{Cite book|title=Federalism, Nationalism and Development: India and the Punjab Economy|date=2008|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134049455|language=English|quote=A large number of Hindu and Muslim peasants converted to Sikhism from conviction, fear, economic motives, or a combination of the three (Khushwant Singh 1999: 106; Ganda Singh 1935: 73).}}
</ref> Mughal rulers of India tortured and executed two of the Sikh gurus—Guru Arjan (1563–1605) and Guru Tegh Bahadur (1621–1675)—after they refused to convert to Islam.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Handbook of Sikh Studies|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-969930-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Martyrdom and the Execution of Guru Arjan in Early Sikh Sources}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Martyrdom and the Sikh Tradition}}
</ref><ref>
{{Cite journal|title=Sikhs and Muslims in the Punjab}}
</ref>
The persecution of Sikhs triggered the founding of the ''Khalsa'' - by Guru Gobind Singh in 1699 - as an order to protect the freedom of conscience and religion,<ref name="Gandhi">{{Cite book|title=History of Sikh Gurus Retold: 1606–1708|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distributors Pvt Ltd|date=1 Feb 2008|isbn=978-8126908578}}</ref> with members expressing the qualities of a '' Sant-Sipāhī''—a 'saint-soldier'.<ref name="Chanchreek 2007 142">{{Cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of Great Festivals|publisher=Shree Publishers & Distributors|isbn=978-8183291910}}</ref><ref name="Dugga 2001 33">{{Cite book|title=Maharaja Ranjit Singh: The Last to Lay Arms|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-8170174103}}</ref>

